<p>This article is a triumph of ideology over experience. Somehow people trying to defend the commons really just &#8216;hate humanity&#8217;. Von Mises would be horified. How can we treat the atmosphere and climate and flowing waters as anything but commons? They don&#8217;t stay put, but we all depend on them. The radical individualism advanced here is (as the author seems to admit, in passing) a recipe for the destruction of any commons. Absolute private property rights in the atmosphere or climate or waters that flow through various regions and are drawn on by individuals and communities for multiple purposes are impossible to establish or defend&#8211; so we&#8217;d better learn to protect the commons (as we&#8217;ve done in many cases already on smaller scales). The alternative is catastrophe.<br/>
Of course a real individualist wouldn&#8217;t care (so long as I&#8217;ve got mine, as the saying goes). But the very fact that denialists have poured so much effort into distorting the evidence and denying AGW make it clear that most people actually care about their children and grandchildren&#8211; and maybe even a little about other people&#8217;s. This is at least a basis for hope, that the nihilism represented by this article will not make it impossible for us to avoid disaster.</p>
